        <name>7.4.5.2 (not in quiz): Gauss elimination method &#9472; inverse of 3 x 3 matrix</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Use the Gauss elimination method to find the inverse of the following matrices&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\[\bf A = {@A@},\] \[\bf B = {@B@}.\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div&gt;(a) \(\bf A^{-1}=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div&gt;(b) \(\bf B^{-1}=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;FEEDBACK&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;We can find the inverse of matrix \(\bf A\) using the Gaussian elimination method.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;We do this by reducing the matrix \(\bf A\) to the identity matrix \(\bf I\).&amp;nbsp;There is no unique procedure for this but here is one example.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;We first place \(\bf A\) and \(\bf I\) adjacent to each other.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;{@A@} {@I@}.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;We now proceed by changing the columns of \(\bf A\) left to right to reduce \(\bf A\) to the form {@upper@},&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;where \(n\) can be any number. This form is called upper triangular.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;First we swap row 1 and row 2.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\[{@A@} {@I@} R1 \leftrightarrow R2 \longrightarrow {@matrixa@} {@I2@}. \]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now we subtract {@a[2,1]@} times row 1 from row 2 and {@a[3,1]@} times row 1 from row 3.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\[{@matrixa@} {@I2@} R2 - {@a[2,1]@} R1, R3 - {@a[3,1]@} R1 \longrightarrow&amp;nbsp;{@matrixb@} {@I3@}.\]&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Then we divide row 2 by {@b[2,2]@} and subtract {@b[3,2]@} times row 2 from row 3.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\[{@matrixb@} {@I3@} R2/{@b[2,2]@}, R3 - {@b[3,2]@} R2 \longrightarrow {@matrixc@} {@I4@}.\]&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Finally we divide row 3 by {@c[3,3]@}.&lt;/p&gt;\[{@matrixc@} {@I4@} R3/{@c[3,3]@} \longrightarrow {@matrixd@} {@I5@}.\]&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;We would usually proceed by changing the columns of \(\bf A\) right to left to reduce \(\bf A\) to the form {@I@}. However, for this question we already obtained zeros above the main diagonal after we swapped row 1 and row 2.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;So we have,&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\[\bf A^{-1} = {@I5@}.\]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The method can be used to determine \(\bf B^{-1}\) similarly, which gives \( B^{-1} = {@ta2@}.\)&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
